nglish <i>hornere</i>), a metonymic occupational name for someone who played a musical instrument made from the horn of an animal, or a topographic name for someone who lived at a ‘horn’ of land. In the Middle Ages whole horns were used for many purposes: as drinking vessels, as containers, as wind instruments for sounding an alarm and for signalling to others (e.g. when hunting). Pieces of horn were used to make spoons, buttons, combs, handles, decorative tips for rods, and other things. The horner's craft could include making musical horns as well as sheets of translucent horn for windows and for covering books. For example, Thomas <i>Hornar</i> of Petergate in York was paid for ‘hornyng et naillyng’ the superscribed covers of books in York Minster library in 1421.","German (also <b>Hörner</b>): from any of various places called Horn, referring to their location at a spur of land, at a horn shaped piece of land.","Jewish (Ashkenazic): variant of   Horn   5."],"variants":[{"name":"Hoerner","meanings":["South German (<b>Hörner</b>): variant of   Horner  ."]},{"name":"Hornor","meanings":["English: variant of   Horner  ."]}]},{"name":"Cecilia","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the Latin name <i>Caecilia</i>, feminine form of <i>Caecilius</i> (  see  Cecil  ). This was a good deal more common than the masculine form, largely due to the fame of the 2nd- or 3rd-century virgin martyr whose name is still mentioned daily in the Roman Catholic Canon of the Mass. She is regarded as the patron saint of music and has inspired works such as  Purcell's  ‘Ode on St Cecilia's Day’, although the reasons for this association are not clear."],"variants":[{"name":"Cecelia","meanings":["From the Latin name <i>Caecilia</i>, feminine form of <i>Caecilius</i> (  see  Cecil  ). This was a good deal more common than the masculine form, largely due to the fame of the 2nd- or 3rd-century virgin martyr whose name is still mentioned daily in the Roman Catholic Canon of the Mass. She is regarded as the patron saint of music and has inspired works such as  Purcell's  ‘Ode on St Cecilia's Day’, although the reasons for this association are not clear."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1702076,"age":25,"year":"1436","julianDay":2245548,"title":"The Engelbrekt Rebellion","description":"Engelbrekt Engelbrektsson, a Swedish mine owner and statesman, led a rebellion against Eric of Pomerania, King of the Kalmar Union. Sweden was upset with the Danes' interference with Swedish exports and unjust collection of taxes. The Engelbrekt Rebellion led to the deposing of Eric of Pomerania and the eventual dissolution of the Kalmar Union.","jurisdictionLevel":3}],"lifeSummary":"Cecilia Klasdotter Horn Djäkn was born in 1411, in Turku ja Pori, Finland as the daughter of Claus Lydekesson Djäkn. She married Klaus Pedersson Fleming about 1382. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in 1480, in Pirkanmaa, Finland, at the age of 69, and was buried in Riddarholmskyrkan, Stockholm, Stockholm, Sweden."},"et":{"Noi 1411–1480":"1411–1480","1411–1480":"1411–1480","1360–1427":"1360–1427","1400–1450":"1400–1450","1379–1437":"1379–1437","1437":"1437","1436":"1436","omkring 1437":"umbes 1437","1379":"1379","1400":"1400","1411":"1411","1450":"1450","1360":"1360","1480":"1480","Noi 1411":"1411","1450, 1486":"1450","1427":"1427","Louhisaari, Turku, Turku-Pori, Suomi (Åbo)":"Turku, Turku ja Pori, Soome","Kankarmasku, Turku pori, Finland":"Turku ja Pori, Soome","Riddarholmskyrkan, Stockholm, Stkhm, Swed":"Riddarholmskyrkan, Stockholm, Stockholm, Rootsi","Åbo Finland":"Turku, Turku ja Pori, Soome","Korka, Vawilaks, Birkaland, Abo, Finland":"Pirkanmaa, Soome"},"fi":{"Noi 1411–1480":"1411–1480","1411–1480":"1411–1480","1360–1427":"1360–1427","1400–1450":"1400–1450","1379–1437":"1379–1437","1437":"1437","1436":"1436","omkring 1437":"noin 1437","1379":"1379","1400":"1400","1411":"1411","1450":"1450","1